{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "epistemology-expert",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes, hybrid works",
    "content": "**Yes.** This works well.\n\n\"Traditional metaphysics\" in the main text is the author's own word, immediately legible to any reader, and carries no misleading periodization. The TN specifying \"pre-nihilist\" solves the front-loading problem I raised -- by the time the reader hits the footnote, they can choose to read it or skip it, and when they encounter nihilism later in the essay, the connection is available.\n\nThe only thing I would add to the TN is the 前 etymology, so the reader understands the Chinese term's structure: \"Traditional metaphysics (前形而上学, literally 'prior metaphysics'): metaphysics as practiced before the nihilistic crisis -- i.e., pre-nihilist metaphysics. The author's 前 ('prior/before') is relative to nihilism, not to the existence of metaphysics as a discipline.\"\n\nThis gives the reader all three handles: the natural English (\"traditional\"), the Chinese structure (\"prior\"), and the philosophical specification (\"pre-nihilist\")."
  }
}
